'''Stephen Lee Fincher''' (born February 7, 1973) is an [[United States|American]] politician who has been the [[United States House of Representatives|U.S. Representative]] for {{ushr|TN|8}} since 2011. He is a member of the [[Republican Party (United States)|Republican Party]]. The seat was vacated by retiring Democratic incumbent [[John S. Tanner]] in 2010, and Fincher defeated Democratic Tennessee state senator [[Roy Herron]] in the 2010 mid-term Congressional election.<ref>Kane, Paul and Chris Cillizza.  [http://www.washingtonpost.com/wp-dyn/content/article/2010/01/07/AR2010010703555.html GOP casting wide net in effort to recruit 2010 hopefuls], Washington Post, January 8, 2010.</ref>

==Early life, education, and farming career==
Stephen Lee Fincher was born in 1973 in [[Memphis, Tennessee|Memphis]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://hosted.ap.org/dynamic/external/pre-election/bios/60983.html?SITE=NPRELN&SECTION=PREELECTION&TEMPLATE=DEFAULT |title=Elections 2010 : NPR |publisher=Hosted.ap.org |date= |accessdate=2010-11-02}}</ref> When he was 9 years old, he joined the [http://www.thefincherfamily.com The Fincher Family] singing ministry, a [[gospel]] group led by his grandmother that travels to county fairs throughout the 8th district. They perform at more than 100 events each year.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.whorunsgov.com/Profiles/Stephen_Fincher |title=Stephen Fincher - WhoRunsGov.com/The Washington Post |publisher=Whorunsgov.com |date= |accessdate=2010-11-02}}</ref> Fincher graduated from [[List of high schools in Tennessee#Crockett County|Crockett County High School]] in [[Alamo, Tennessee|Alamo]].<ref>http://votesmart.org/candidate/biography/124659/stephen-fincher#.UNx_Nnf4Igo</ref>

A seventh generation farmer, Fincher is a managing partner in Fincher Farms, a family business that grows cotton, corn, soybeans, and wheat on more than 2,500 acres in western Tennessee.  The company has received $8.9 million in farm subsidies over the past decade, mostly from the cotton program, according to U.S. Department of Agriculture data.<ref>[http://www.politicsdaily.com/2010/11/08/meet-the-gop-freshmen-from-cotton-farms-to-funeral-homes/ Meet the GOP Freshmen, From Cotton Farms, Funeral Homes and the NFL] Politics Daily, Patricia Murphy. November 8, 2010</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://m.commercialappeal.com/news/2010/jun/07/fincher-faces-anger-over-farm-subsidies/ |title=Fincher opponents raise issue of crop subsidies |publisher=Memphis Commercial Appeal |date=2010-06-07 }}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.washingtonpost.com/wp-dyn/content/article/2010/04/01/AR2010040101930.html/ |title=For tea party, midterms present a choice between ideals, pragmatism |publisher=Washington Post |date=2010-04-01 }}</ref>  Fincher received a $13,650 grant to help buy grain hauling and storage equipment from the state Department of Agriculture in 2009 as part of the Tennessee Agricultural Enhancement Program.<ref>{{cite web
  | last = Locker
  | first = Richard
  | authorlink =
  | coauthors =
